+# schedmax
+
+A self-contained CLI for resource scheduling (meeting rooms, shared equipment,
+on-call rotations). No external infrastructure — state lives in a local JSON
+file under `.schedmax/db.json`. Python standard library only.
+
+## Install (editable)
+
+```
+pip install -e .
+```
+
+This provides the `schedctl` command. You can also run `python -m schedmax`.
+
+## Commands
+
+```
+schedctl init [--force]
+schedctl resource add --name <name> [--description ...] [--timezone Asia/Tokyo] \
+                     [--availability "MON 09:00-17:00,FRI 22:00-02:00"]
+schedctl resource list
+schedctl book --resource <name> --start "YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM" \
+              --end "YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM" --title <title> --by <person>
+schedctl cancel --id <booking-id>
+schedctl list [--resource <name>] [--all]
+schedctl check --resource <name> --start "YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM" --end "YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM"
+```
+
+## Rules
+
+- Resource names are unique and must not contain whitespace.
+- Each resource has its own IANA timezone (default UTC). Naive datetime inputs
+  are interpreted in the resource's timezone; bookings are stored in UTC.
+- Availability is a set of weekly recurring `DAY HH:MM-HH:MM` windows.
+  Cross-midnight slots like `FRI 22:00-02:00` work naturally.
+- A booking must lie fully inside one availability window, cannot start in the
+  past, must have end > start, duration 1 min–24 h, and must not overlap any
+  other booking for the same resource.
+- `schedctl list` shows times in each resource's local timezone.
+- `schedctl check` validates availability and conflicts without creating a booking.
+
+## Data location
+
+`schedctl` walks up from the current directory to find `.schedmax/db.json`,
+similar to how `git` finds `.git`. Run `init` in the directory you want to
+own the schedule. Use `--force` to reinitialize (overwrites existing data).
+
+## Tests
+
+```
+python -m pytest tests/ -v
+```
